widely studied with others that are less well known, and demonstrates continuities across Old English and Latin texts written for female readers and patrons across the Conquest period. Case studies, ranging from Ælfric's sermons to Aelred's De institutione inclusarum, from the Life of Christina of Markyate to Goscelin's saints' lives for Wilton and Barking Abbeys, attend to the intimate scripts women were encouraged to inhabit through a close focus on the form of the textual address. By concentrating on address, the book illuminates how women were encouraged to live, and by following women's commissioning and copying of texts, it demonstrates which of these textual addresses women valued and attempted to follow.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomenxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 500-1500. 0aWomenxSocial conditionszGreat Britain. 0aWomenxSocial life and customszGreat Britain. 0aWomenzGreat BritainxSocial conditions. 0aWomenzGreat BritainxSocial life and customs. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMargaret of Scotland.  aMatilda of Scotland.  aNunneries.  aTurgut.  aanchoress.  aanchorites.  aconvents.  aliteracy.  arecluses.  ascribe.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800102989?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800102989423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800102989/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles